{"id":"1904.01233","submitter":"Demitry Farfurnik","authors":"Demitry Farfurnik and Nir Bar-Gill","title":"Characterizing spin-bath parameters using conventional and\n  time-asymmetric Hahn-echo sequences","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. B 101, 104306 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.101.104306","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph cond-mat.mes-hall","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Spin-bath noise characterization, which is typically performed by multi-pulse\ncontrol sequences, is essential for understanding most spin dynamics in the\nsolid-state. Here, we theoretically propose a method for extracting the\ncharacteristic parameters of a noise source with a known spectrum, using a\nsingle modified Hahn-echo sequence. By varying the application time of the\npulse, measuring the coherence curves of an addressable spin, and fitting the\ndecay coefficients to a theoretical function derived by us, we extract\nparameters characterizing the physical nature of the noise. Assuming a\nLorentzian noise spectrum, we illustrate this method for extracting the\ncorrelation time of a bath of nitrogen paramagnetic impurities in diamond, and\nits coupling strength to the addressable spin of a nitrogen-vacancy center.\nConsidering a realistic experimental scenario with $5\\%$ measurement error, the\nparameters can be extracted with an accuracy of $\\sim 10 \\%$. The scheme is\neffective for samples having a natural homogeneous coherence time ($T_2$) up to\ntwo orders of magnitude greater than the inhomogeneous coherence time\n($T_2^*$), and mitigates technical noise when further averaging is irrelevant.\nBeyond its potential for reducing experiment times by an order-of-magnitude,\nsuch single-pulse noise characterization could minimize the effects of long\ntime-scale drifts and accumulating pulse imperfections and numerical errors.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 2 Apr 2019 06:43:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 23 Jul 2019 12:55:56 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 1 Feb 2020 20:54:08 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-03-18"}
